Text.Value: You know me.
And more. I am Vlaakith's eyes in darkness, her ears in chaos. I am law. I am judgement!
Tell me more of this Orpheus.

EditorData.stateContext: Voss is kneeling, sword laid across the ground.

Text.Value: Such informality, child. Does Jhe'stil Kith'rak not command your respect?

EditorData.NodeContext: zhe-STILL KITH-rack. Supreme Knight. Fatherly, but not antagonsistically like before.

Text.Value: 'Live, but only if you live free' - Gith's plea to us all. I will know my prince. This is my path.
Do as you will, Lae'zel. I won't stand in your way.
Gith made our people free. But it was Vlaakith who made us mighty.
Gith made your people free. But it was Vlaakith who made them mighty.
Yes. Yes! I will be pure. I will ascend. I will wield silver!
Heresy! My Queen is truth.
But her son lives, child. He lives! The flame of our freedom, burning in your hand. Together -

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Fahra lunges towards Voss and tries to attack, but she misses.

Text.Value: *You recall this name: 'Fahra'. No mere warrior or even kith'rak, but Vlaakith's Hand - enforcer of your Queen's will.*
Then you've been blinded to Orpheus' light.
I am Vlaakith's judgement!
Child. You are a slave. Chained, bound, and beaten by the Queen of Lies.
Vlaakith does not love you. There is no ascension, no purification. You are cattle, you are chaff - to be harvested and devoured.
Quedenos. Ignis magma!

EditorData.NodeContext: Called out to the dragon, preparing to fight.

EditorData.stateContext: Voss is wounded on the ground.

Text.Value: Supreme Kith'rak. Have you come to slay me with your own silver?
A myth, recorded to slate, fed to us like devils to dragons.
Quedenos - at my command!
Fool! Reject Orpheus, or I will present your head to Vlaakith myself.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: A portal opens and a few Githyanki, including Vlaakith's Hand, name of Fahra, exit out of it and move to surround the party.

Text.Value: It is time we abandon Vlaakith, Lae'zel. Show Fahra your might.
Abandon Vlaakith, Lae'zel. Cut Fahra down.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Voss grabs his sword and rises to his feet

Text.Value: Vlaakith made us slaves.
Gith's spirit lives on in her son. He deserves your allegiance.
Who in the hells are you?
Fahra.
Orpheus.
No. I will not turn on my Queen!

EditorData.NodeContext: Addressed to player, but uncertain despite her words.

Text.Value: I am Gith's child. I bend to Vlaakith no longer.
And yet Vlaakith prepares you a place at her table.
Lae'zel. You will not be our ruin. Orpheus will rise. The githyanki will be free.

EditorData.NodeContext: Addressed to Lae'zel. Sad but determined.

Text.Value: Son of Gith, our great mother. Vlaakith calls him traitor. I call him saviour.
'Fahra'. Vlaakith's Hand, her Eyes, her Voice.
Have you already forgotten? Did my own Queen not turn her back?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Fahra lunges towards Voss and attacks. Wounded, he falls to the ground.

Text.Value: You mean nothing to Vlaakith. Reject her, and seek the truth.

EditorData.stateContext: Voss is on his feet, holding his sword

Text.Value: Mother Gith did not tear off our shackles for our flesh to feed a new master!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The dragon rears up and roars at the party.

Text.Value: Your cronies tried to kill us. Why should Lae'zel listen to you?

EditorData.logicalname: Gith tried to kill Lae'zel before

Text.Value: K'chakhi! I name you hshar'lak - traitor to your people. It is written!
My queen calls. I am prepared to answer.
The relic you carry, the one Vlaakith hunts. I know its truth. The heart of my people beats within it.
Fahrah. You are Vlaakith's Hand.
Vlaakith's puppet.
Quedenos - at my command!
K'chakhi! I name you hshar'lak - traitor to your people. It is written!
Tl'a'vlaakith - I will not be bound my flame, rider!

EditorData.logicalname: Player is meeting Voss for the first time

Text.Value: Very well. Remain loyal to Vlaakith, and bear the consequences.
Orpheus. Impossible. The traitor is dead.
I knew not then what I know now. Let the truth be my atonement.
And so it is. It holds the true heir, it holds insurrection - a blade to be held against Vlaakith's withered throat.
Shabell'eth. I will listen, as is my duty.
Go on then. Speak.
Fine. We'll hear what you have to say before we gut you.
No!

EditorData.NodeContext: Lae'zel calling out after Farah strikes Voss down

Text.Value: Lae'zel. The pride of Crèche K'liir.
My eyes were open, and I refused to see. My ears heard, and still I turned away. But I will be slave no more.
Her word is your duty, her will is your honour. Strike down the kith'rak, deliver the relic - and claim your seat at our Queen's side. Be ascended!
Speak. My ear is yours.
Orpheus - Gith's son. I thought he was long dead.
*Orpheus, a name of legend. The son of Gith, the first leader of your people, executed by exalted Queen Vlaakith - or so you were taught.*
|A githyanki prince? Is this why the mother superior seeks this relic?|
Then I turn to the True Heir.
Tsk'va! Lae'zel, with me!
No. I will be slave no longer!
I've been inside. There was no githyanki prince there.
My eyes were open, and I refused to see. My ears heard, and still I turned away. But I will be slave no more.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Voss kneels and lays his sword on the ground in the githyanki sign of submission.

Text.Value: Renounce Vlaakith if you must, then. But be prepared for the consequences.
Yes. Yes! 'Beware the lies of false prophets.' So said the exalted Queen. And so I will heed!
The Absolute's army marches. We need Vlaakith on our side.
I thought the artefact was a weapon.
We are servants of Vlaakith. Killing Voss is the way forward.
You are a servant of Vlaakith. Killing Voss is the only way forward.
I heard truth in the kith'rak's words. I trust him, and so should you.
You. I lend you my might, my very essence, and you thwart my will at every turn!
*Lae'zel's loyalty wavers. You feel her confusion, her uncertainty - and a nascent longing for freedom.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Mind meld between Lae'zel and player, but no need to show anyone's hands go to their heads, just the VFX is fine.

Text.Value: Quedenos chyrki. Ch'mar, zal'a Vlaakith!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Fahra weaves a psionic spell and casts it on Voss's dragon, making it fight for her.

Text.Value: You might have killed us before. Why should Lae'zel listen to you?

EditorData.logicalname: Gith tried to kill Lae'zel before

Text.Value: Vlaakith is my path. Ascension is my fate!
Your blood? No, child. I've come for your aid.
Nod to Lae'zel. She should take the lead.
Say nothing.
*Lae'zel's loyalty to Vlaakith burns her mind - and yours. She means to strike Kith'rak Voss.*

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Mind meld between Lae'zel and player, but no need to show anyone's hands go to their heads, just the VFX is fine.

Text.Value: I know you. Your Queen knows you. A nova among stars.
Handle this, Lae'zel.
Your flame speaks for you, kith'rak. You've come for blood.
Do not dare speak my name!
Voss. My Queen serves you feast and favour - and you repay her with treason.
That doesn't explain why you came for our heads.
I know my allegiance. It is to my Queen!
I've not come to kill you, child. I've come to free you.
Truth. So tainted by death and deceit that I'd forgotten its taste.

EditorData.NodeContext: Addressed to player, but more a musing to herself. She has come to see the player's point of view.

Text.Value: I see it - your great will, your great strength, a gift from Vlaakith herself.
Ska'kek kir Gith shabell'eth. My blade rests. Mother Gith compels you to listen.
I know you. Your Queen knows you. You are ice, you are brimstone, stained with your kin's blood.
Pitiful kith'rak. Your lies sting like acid and burn like flame. I name you hshar'lak - traitor!
Because I know the truth of your relic. It holds the very heart and soul of our people.
Your ear is all I ask. But I will take your head if I must.
You've trapped us in flame. Why in the Hells should I listen to you?
Prince Orpheus lives. And it is his prison you carry.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The dragon rears up and roars at the party.

Text.Value: So it is written! To arms, Lae'zel. Let the traitors taste blood and silver!
Keep talking.
'Live, but only if you live free' - Gith's plea to us all. I will know my prince. This is my path.
I know of the relic you carry, child - and I know its truth. It holds the very heart and soul of our people.
I've not come to kill you, Lae'zel. I've come to free you.
Quedenos chyrki. Ch'mar, zal'a Vlaakith!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Fahra weaves a psionic spell and casts it on Voss's dragon, making it fight for her.

Synopsis: The player must pick between siding with Voss and helping Orpheus or siding with Vlaakith's Inquisitor in killing Orpheus. Laezel is predisposed to a certain faction depending on the outcome of the Creche, but can be convinced by the player to swing to the other faction. A fight results with the opposing party and Laezel can leave the party and be hostile if not convinced to side with the Player's decision.
